2026-04-16 12:10:04 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['inter-module cable connection between power supply module and control module'] hypothesis_explanation='The power supply indicator LED is on, proving the PSU and its polarity locally are correct. The red inverted-cables indicator LED in the control module being lit means that, relative to the control module’s internal reference, the incoming 12 V and 0 V lines are swapped. The visual inspection confirmed that the PSU’s + output is connected to the control module’s − input, and the PSU’s − output is connected to the control module’s + input. This wiring inversion both lights the control-module LED (by intentionally forward-biasing its ‘wrong polarity’ circuit) and prevents proper operation of the downstream load (and its diode), so the lamp never turns on. Correcting this misconnection—so PSU + goes to control +, and PSU − goes to control −—should restore normal lamp operation when the switch is closed.'
